<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-field-generated-by" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Field generated by a subset</title>
    <p>
        We begin by defining an <m>F</m>-algebra, where <m>F</m> is a field.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-F-algebra">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>F</m> be a field. An <m>F</m>-algebra or an algebra over a field <m>F</m> is an associative ring <m>A</m> with unity together with a ring homomorphism <m>\varphi\colon F\to Z(A)</m>. The ring <m>A</m> is also given an <m>F</m>-vector space structure by defining the scalar multiplication <m>\alpha\cdot a\mapsto \varphi(\alpha)a</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <observation>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>A</m> is an <m>F</m>-algebra. Then, <m>A</m> is both a ring and an <m>F</m>-vector space. Furthermore, the ring and vector space structures are compatible, i.e., for <m>\alpha\in F</m> and <m>a,b\in A</m> we have the following.
                <md>
                    <mrow>\alpha\cdot(ab) \amp =\varphi(\alpha)(ab)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =(\varphi(\alpha)a)b</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =(\alpha\cdot a)b</mrow>
                </md>
                Similarly, we have the following by using the fact that <m>\varphi(\alpha)\in Z(A)</m>.
                <md>
                    <mrow>\alpha\cdot(ab) \amp =\varphi(\alpha)(ab)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =(\varphi(\alpha)a)b</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =(a\varphi(\alpha))b</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =a(\varphi(\alpha)b)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =a(\alpha\cdot b)</mrow>
                </md>    
            </p>
            
            <p>
                Therefore,
            <men xml:id="eqn-algebra-compatibility">
                \alpha\cdot(ab)=(\alpha\cdot a)b=a(\alpha\cdot b)
            </men>
            </p>            
    </observation>
    <observation>
        <p>
            Note that for <m>\alpha\in F</m> and <m>a\in A</m> we have <m>(\alpha\cdot 1_A)a=\alpha\cdot a</m>. Also, <m>a(\alpha\cdot 1_A)=\alpha\cdot a</m>. Hence, <m>(\alpha\cdot 1_A)a=a(\alpha\cdot 1_A)</m>.
        </p>
    </observation>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>F</m> be a field. Then, the polynomial ring <m>F[x]</m> is an <m>F</m>-algebra.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The ring of <m>n\times n</m> matrices with entries in <m>F</m>, denoted by <m>M_n(F)</m>, is an <m>F</m>-algebra.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>E/F</m> is a field extension, then <m>E</m> is an <m>F</m>-algebra.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-algebra-homomorphism">
        <title>Algebra homomorphism</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>F</m> is a field and that <m>A,B</m> are <m>F</m>-algebras. An <m>F</m>-algebra homomorphism from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> is a ring homomorphism as well as an <m>F</m>-linear map.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="ex-evaluation-map-as-algebra-homomorphism">
        <title>Evaluation as an algebra homomorphism</title>
        
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>E/F</m> be a field extension, and let <m>\alpha\in E</m>. The evaluation map <m>\ev_\alpha\colon F[x]\to E</m> given by <m>p(x)\mapsto p(\alpha)</m> is an <m>F</m>-algebra homomorphism.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-field-generated-by-a-subset">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>E/F</m> be an extension of fields and <m>X</m> be a subset of <m>E</m>. 
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The ring generated by <m>X</m> is the intersection of all subrings of <m>E</m> containing <m>X</m>, denoted by <m>F[X]</m>. If <m>X=\{a_1,a_2,\cdots,a_n\}</m> then, we write <m>F[X]=F[a_1,a_2,\cdots,a_n]</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The field generated by <m>X</m> is the intersection of all subfields of <m>E</m> containing <m>X</m>, denoted by <m>F(X)</m>. If <m>X=\{a_1,a_2,\cdots,a_n\}</m> then, we write <m>F(X)=F(a_1,a_2,\cdots,a_n)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-field-generated-by-a-subset">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>E/F</m> be a field extension, and let <m>a\in E</m>. Then, <me>
                    F[a]=\{p(a):p(x)\in F[x]\}
                </me> and 
                <me>
                    F(a)=\left\{p(a)/q(a):p(x),q(x)\in F[x],\text{ and }q(a)\neq 0\right\}.
                </me>
                
                
            </p>
        </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Consider the evaluation <m>F</m>-algebra homomorphism <m>{\mathrm ev}_a\colon F[x]\to E</m> given by <m>p(x)\mapsto p(a)</m>. The image of this homomorphism is a subring of <m>E</m> containing <m>a</m>. By the closure of addition and multiplication the image of <m>{\mathrm ev}_a</m> is contained in every subring of <m>E</m> containing <m>F</m> and <m>a</m>. Thus, the image of <m>{\mathrm ev}_a</m> is the ring generated by <m>a</m>, i.e., <m>F[a]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            A similar argument shows the statement about <m>F(a)</m>.
        </p>
    </proof>
</section>